[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":483},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F12\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-36-fps\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F12\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-36-fps\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F12\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-36-fps\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F12\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-36-fps\u002F":458,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F12\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-36-fps\u002F":467},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20201012\u002F1084963489\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":439,"date":440,"description":441,"extension":442,"lang":443,"meta":444,"navigation":138,"path":445,"readingMinutes":446,"seo":447,"standalone":448,"stem":449,"tags":450,"tldr":455,"updated":440,"url":456,"__hash__":457},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-36-fps.md","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (36) — Adding an FPS Counter to Your Game","1001924320",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":433},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,32,35,46,50,59,62,202,205,216,230,233,275,278,399,409,413,429],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"We've finished a decent chunk of the Treasure Hunter game by now, so this feels like a good moment to talk about something PIXI keeps bringing up — FPS.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"whats-fps","What's FPS?",[17,25,26,27,31],{},"FPS is a really important thing in games, and you've probably seen the term in video stuff too. Basically it's how many frames get shown each second. Once that frame rate hits a certain point, things start to feel alive — your brain reads them as one continuous motion even though they're separate frames. The fancy term for this is ",[28,29,30],"strong",{},"persistence of vision",". It's why those old films were literally strips of individual frames: play them back fast enough and your eyes see smooth, connected motion.",[17,33,34],{},"That said, a super high frame rate isn't automatically better either — push it too far and you can actually get screen tearing.",[17,36,37,38,45],{},"If you want the deeper explanation, the ",[39,40,44],"a",{"href":41,"rel":42},"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FFrame_rate",[43],"nofollow","Wikipedia article on frame rate"," covers it much more thoroughly.",[12,47,49],{"id":48},"adding-an-fps-counter-to-treasure-hunter","Adding an FPS counter to Treasure Hunter",[17,51,52,53,58],{},"Next up, we're going to add an FPS counter to the game we built earlier, and for that we'll use a library called ",[39,54,57],{"href":55,"rel":56},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fmrdoob\u002Fstats.js\u002F",[43],"stats.js",".",[17,60,61],{},"Using it is honestly pretty simple — you basically just paste in the code from the official repo:",[63,64,69],"pre",{"className":65,"code":66,"language":67,"meta":68,"style":68},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var stats = new Stats();\nstats.showPanel(0); \u002F\u002F 0: fps, 1: ms, 2: mb, 3+: custom\ndocument.body.appendChild(stats.dom);\n\nfunction animate() {\n  stats.begin();\n  \u002F\u002F monitored code goes here\n  stats.end();\n  requestAnimationFrame(animate);\n}\nrequestAnimationFrame(animate);\n","js","",[70,71,72,98,121,133,140,152,163,169,179,188,194],"code",{"__ignoreMap":68},[73,74,77,81,85,88,91,95],"span",{"class":75,"line":76},"line",1,[73,78,80],{"class":79},"sWyjQ","var",[73,82,84],{"class":83},"sMAXC"," stats ",[73,86,87],{"class":79},"=",[73,89,90],{"class":79}," new",[73,92,94],{"class":93},"sj_SG"," Stats",[73,96,97],{"class":83},"();\n",[73,99,101,104,107,110,114,117],{"class":75,"line":100},2,[73,102,103],{"class":83},"stats.",[73,105,106],{"class":93},"showPanel",[73,108,109],{"class":83},"(",[73,111,113],{"class":112},"sCcAr","0",[73,115,116],{"class":83},"); ",[73,118,120],{"class":119},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 0: fps, 1: ms, 2: mb, 3+: custom\n",[73,122,124,127,130],{"class":75,"line":123},3